You are given the variable <get_day_calendar_events_1/> which contains the calendar events for 2024-05-19 as a list. Each event object may include fields such as "title", "start_time", "end_time", "description", "location", and "participants". Times may be in ISO format like "2024-05-19 09:30" or similar.

Determine whether the user is free for the interval 2024-05-19 12:00 to 2024-05-19 13:00 (treat interval as [12:00,13:00), local timezone). An event conflicts if it overlaps that interval at all.

Return ONLY a JSON object (ASCII only) matching this schema exactly:
{
  "free": boolean,
  "conflicts": [
    {
      "index": int,                    // 1-based index of the event in the list as provided in <get_day_calendar_events_1/>
      "start_minute": int,             // event start time as minutes since midnight
      "end_minute": int                // event end time as minutes since midnight
    }
  ]
}

If there are no conflicts, return "conflicts": []. Do not include any other fields or text. Compute minutes assuming times are on 2024-05-19 local day. If an event has no end_time or start_time, ignore it for conflict detection. Use integers only for minutes. Output JSON only.

